  	<h2>Enduring Power of Attorney</h2>
	<p>	Enduring Powers of Attorney (which will in due course be replaced by Lasting Powers of Attorney) are a far better alternative to having your financial affairs administered when you are no longer able to deal with these personally.</p>
	<p>Lasting Powers of Attorney, (due to commence from April 2007) will not be limited to empowering others to make decisions on your financial affairs on your behalf. Unlike Enduring Powers of Attorney, they will be registerable on execution, rather than at a stage when mental capacity of the donor begins to diminish.  They will also make provision for the making of health care decisions after mental capacity has been lost.</p>
	<h2>Advice and information on Enduring Powers of Attorney</h2>
      <h3>What  is an Enduring Power of Attorney</h3>
An Enduring Power of Attorney (EPA) is a  legal document that enables someone (the 'donor') to appoint one or more people  ('attorneys'), to manage their financial affairs and property, either now or at  a future date. <br />
<h3>Who can make  one?</h3>
Anyone can make one, provided they are mentally capable of understanding the meaning and effect of the EPA.  This is important, and if anyone has doubts about whether someone has the  capacity to make an EPA, they should seek advice or guidance from a solicitor  or a doctor. <br />
<h3>How do I make an  EPA?</h3>
An EPA must be made using a prescribed form that can be obtained from the PGO and also solicitors. The form to be used is defined within the Enduring Power of Attorney (Prescribed Form) Regulations. Advice on any individual terms or conditions to be included  should be obtained from a legal or other professional adviser. Please note that  staff at the PGO are not legally qualified and therefore cannot provide legal  advice. <br />
<h3>What must be  included in an EPA?</h3>
<p>An EPA must contain three parts: 
<ul>
  <li>Part A: consists of notes to the donor and the attorney concerning an  attorney's powers. <em>Part A must not be detached as it is part of the  form.</em><br /><br /></li>
  <li>Part B: is where the donor appoints the attorney(s).<br /><br /></li>
  <li>Part C: is for the attorney to read and complete, accepting the appointment. Part C must be completed by every attorney as soon as possible after the donor completes Part B.
Care should be taken when completing the form, following all advice and notes very carefully. Incorrectly completed EPAs may not be valid when the time comes  for them to be used. <br /><br /></li>
</ul>
<h3>Registering an EPA</h3>
<p>
An attorney does not have to register an EPA  with the PGO in order to use it, unless the EPA includes a condition requiring  this. However, the attorney must apply to register the Power when there  is reason to believe that the donor is, or is becoming, mentally incapable of  managing his or her own financial affairs. The registration process is  straightforward. It involves an attorney sending a 'Notice of Intention to  Register', using form EP1, to relatives of the donorand giving a form EP1 to the donor, and an application form EP2 is completed. The attorney must then send the <em>original</em> EPA document, together with form EP2 and an application fee to the EPA team at the Public Guardianship Office.</p>
<p>
Detailed information on this procedure is  available in the FAQs section concerning Registration. The registration process  usually takes five weeks. This is to allow time for everyone who has  received a Notice of the attorney's intention, to consider and decide if they  want to register an objection to the application. The PGO waits a statutory 35 days from the date the last notice was sent or given before it formally  registers the EPA.</p>
<h3>What are the risks with an EPA and  what precautions can be taken?</h3>
<p>
An EPA is a very powerful legal document. Potential donors should therefore  think carefully about the responsibilities they are giving to attorney(s). An  attorney can have wide powers and is not&nbsp; supervised in their dealings  with the donor's affairs. As a precaution against potential misuse,  consideration should therefore be given to appointing more than one attorney,  appointing attorneys to always act jointly (rather than jointly and severally),  or to adding restrictions or conditions to the EPA. Another precaution is to  include a requirement that the attorney present annual accounts to a solicitor  or accountant, enabling their actions be monitored. Solicitors, or other  professional advisors, should be able to advise on the various options that a  donor may wish to include. </p><p>
It is worth noting that an EPA can normally  be used as soon as the document is completed. If it is intended that the Power  should not be used until after the donor becomes mentally incapable of managing  their affairs, then an appropriate restriction should be included. Legal advice  should be sought on how to achieve this.
</p>
<h3>Restrictions on the actions an attorney can take</h3>
<p>
Whether an EPA is registered or unregistered, an attorney's powers to make  gifts of money or property to themselves or to others are very limited. If  an attorney acting under a registered EPA is in any doubt whether s/he can make  gifts to her/himself or to others, or whether s/he can use the Power for the  benefit of her/himself or others, s/he must seek advice from the PGO, or from  solicitors or other professional advisors. </p><p>
An attorney has a duty under common law to  keep accounts. The Court of Protection can call on attorneys to account for  their dealings at any time where the EPA is registered or where it needs to be  registered. </p>
<h3>Concerns about the improper use of an EPA</h3>
<p>
If anyone has concerns that an attorney  may not be acting in the donor's best interests under an EPA, this should be  brought to the attention of the Court of Protection. This can be done by  writing to the PGO with all available information concerning the situation. The  Court of Protection will consider the expressed concerns and if it shares  these, will direct that enquiries be made. </p><p>
However, the Court and the PGO only have  powers to look into the possible misuse of an EPA once it is registered, or  where it is clear that the EPA needs to be registered. </p>
	<h3>Finding out if an EPA is registered</h3>
	<p>
      To confirm if an EPA is registered,  the PGO can make a search of relevant records. This requires a completed form EP4 and a search fee is payable.</p>
